abstract_ssm: Daniel Cassidy (1943-2008), Irish-American writer, singer, filmmaker, and professor.  Beginning his career as a musician and screenwriter, Cassidy later turned his interests towards research and academia, focusing on storytelling, newspaper writing, and broadcast history.  A prolific writer, Cassidy's works include numerous newspaper and journal articles, as well as the book How the Irish Invented Slang: The Secret Language of the Crossroads.  Materials in this collection include notes, manuscript drafts, annotated newspapers, play scripts, census documents, and annotated research files.  The material primarily documents Cassidy's research interests and film work, with smaller portions concerning his personal life and his time with both the New College of California and the Crossroads Irish American Festival.
